article.description: Michael Olowokandi had 24 points and 12 rebounds, and Elton Brand scored 17 points as the Los Angeles Clippers snapped a three-game losing streak with a 99-89 victory Monday night over the Golden State Warriors.
article.headline: Olowokandi, Brand get Clippers past Warriors
article.linkText: Clippers play some D, end skid vs. Warriors
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Michael Olowokandi needed 24 minutes to figure out how to beat the Golden State Warriors. He spent the next 24 minutes showing off what he learned.
Olowokandi

Brand

Olowokandi had 24 points and 12 rebounds, and Elton Brand scored 17 points as the Los Angeles Clippers snapped a three-game losing streak with a 99-89 victory Monday night over the Warriors. After Olowokandi and coach Alvin Gentry decided to put the ball in the big center's hands throughout the second half, he responded with 20 points after halftime, repeatedly hurting the Warriors with short hook shots in his highest-scoring game of the season. ''I was slow coming out of the block, but once I recognized what they were doing, we made an effort to get it inside and get short, easy shots,'' Olowokandi said. ''Whenever you have a balanced attack, it's difficult for teams to stay with you. We changed some things, and we got a lot more open looks.'' Though he shows flashes of brilliance, Olowokandi never has lived up to his potential as the first overall draft pick in 1998. But performances such as this one illustrate why he'll be a sought-after free agent when his one-year contract with the Clippers ends next summer. Playing their fourth game in five nights, the Clippers also improved the poor defense that caused their 3-7 start, holding Golden State under 35 percent shooting. Corey Maggette added 16 points as Los Angeles took a 19-point lead in the third quarter and maintained a double-digit margin in the fourth. ''For us, it's all about where our strengths are,'' Gentry said. ''Tonight, we had a tendency to stay with those strengths. We just kept getting the ball down to Michael and Elton. It was a win that we desperately needed. We have enough problems as it is. We don't need to lose games like this one.'' The Clippers also showed signs of a fast break, which hadn't been the case in many games this season. They blew a 15-point lead against Seattle on Sunday night, chiefly because they played poor transition offense and defense. ''Once we got a 15-point lead again, we didn't want to do what we did last night,'' Brand said. ''They send a lot of guys to the boards, so we knew we could get out and run when we weren't concentrating on our set offense.'' Los Angeles easily held off the inept Warriors, who regressed dramatically from the form they showed in a 135-92 victory over Orlando on Saturday night -- the franchise's biggest win in nearly nine years. Golden State had its worst shooting game of the season. Antawn Jamison scored 26 points, and Erick Dampier had 17 rebounds as the Warriors lost for the ninth time in 11 games to remain last in the Pacific Division. ''I don't know what's going on, but this was a game that we definitely should have had,'' Jamison said. ''From the get-go, guys just didn't come out and play like it was needed. I don't think that guys recognize the urgency of these games at home.'' Mike Dunleavy scored 15 points in the best game of his rookie season with Golden State, but the Warriors fell behind early and managed only one feeble attempt at a comeback while showing none of the offensive flair and defensive toughness they exhibited at the start of their five-game homestand. ''As great as the other night was, it was that bad tonight,'' Warriors coach Eric Musselman said. ''They beat us to loose balls, they out-executed us and they outworked us. We bobbled balls. We shot 34 percent.'' Golden State opened the third quarter with a 14-6 run led by Jamison and Gilbert Arenas to pull within six, but Olowokandi scored eight points as the Clippers responded with a 15-2 run, giving them a 73-58 lead entering the fourth. Warriors starting guards Arenas and Jason Richardson struggled, but backups Dean Oliver and Jiri Welsch were no better; the four players were a combined 7-for-28 from the field. Arenas fouled out with 7:42 to play, while Richardson finished with four points -- his worst game in 10 months. Game notes
A.J. Guyton, signed by the Warriors earlier in the day, got into the game in the second quarter after Oliver struggled in place of Arenas. ... Dampier got eight rebounds in the game's first 4 minutes. ... Raiders receiver Jerry Rice was dismayed when he discovered that his tickets were for the third row, not courtside. Former 49ers running back Roger Craig had courtside seats.
